Creating a GitHub Account and Setting Up Git in Linux
1. Install Git
$ sudo apt install git
This installs Git on the system.
2. Configure Git with User Details
$ git config --global user.name "Pragatika Mishra"
$ git config --global user.email "pragatika.mishra23_ug@gmail.com"
This sets up your Git identity for commits. 
3. Initialize a Repository
$ git init myrep
Creates a new Git repository named myrep.
4. Navigate to the Repository
$ cd myrep
Moves into the repository directory.
5. Remove an Existing Directory (If Needed)
rm -rf Pragatika
Deletes the folder named Pragatika.
6. Create or Edit Files Using Pico (Nano)
$ pico file0.text
Opens file0.text in the Pico (Nano) text editor for editing
7. Add a File to the Repository
git add file0.text
Stages the file for commit. 
8. Check the Status of the Repository
$ git status
Shows the current state of the repository.
9. View Git Repository History (Graphical Interface)
gitk
Opens GitK, a visual history viewer for Git repositories
10. Check Installed Git Version
git --version
Displays the installed Git version. 
Summary
- Installed Git and configured user details.
- Created a repository and added files.
- Checked Git status and history using git status and gitk.
- Used Pico (Nano) for file editing and git add for tracking changes.
